  "pride_metadata": {
    "project": {
      "accession": "PXD054186",
      "title": "The changes in cetuximab resistant HNSCC cell lines (e.g., OECM1-cetuximabR and CAL-27 cetuximabR) after being treated with Cetuximab (500 ug/ml) for at least 2 months. We used LC-MS/MS to identify the main phosphorylation sites in resistance cell lines.",
      "additionalAttributes": [],
      "projectDescription": "Recent clinical trials revealed that prior use of Cetuximab may interfere with ICB efficacy. In this study, STAT1 protein levels changed after continued Cetuximab treatment (500 ug/ml). We used LC-MS/MS to compare the phosphorylation sites in wild-type and resistant cells. We proposed that the phosphorylation of STAT1 may lead to the degradation of the STAT1 protein.",
      "sampleProcessingProtocol": "In-sol digestion. The immunoprecipitation products were first eluted from beads, dried under vacuum, and reconstituted with 6 M urea/50 mM ammonium bicarbonate (ABC). The eluted proteins were reduced with 5 mM dithiothreitol (DTT, Merck) at 37\u00b0C for 90 min, followed by cysteine-blocking with 10 mM iodoacetamide (IAM, Sigma) at 25\u00b0C for 30 min. Samples were diluted with 25 mM ABC and digested withGlu-cat 37\u00b0C for 16 hours.  LC-MS/MS analysis. The TiO2-enriched peptides were diluted in HPLC buffer A (0.1% formic acid) and loaded onto a reverse-phase column (Zorbax 300SB-C18, 0.3 \u00d7 5 mm; Agilent Technologies). The desalted peptides were then separated on a homemade column (HydroRP 2.5 \u00b5m, 75 \u03bcm I.D. \u00d7 20 cm with a 15 \u03bcm tip) using a multi-step gradient of HPLC buffer B (99.9% acetonitrile/0.1% formic acid) for 90 minutes with a flow rate of 0.3 \u03bcl/min. The LC apparatus was coupled with Orbitrap Elite MS (Thermo Fisher Scientific) operated using Xcalibur 2.2. The full-scan MS was performed in the Orbitrap over a range of 400 to 2,000 Da and a resolution of 120,000 at m/z 400. Internal calibration was performed using the ion signal of protonated dodecamethylcyclohexasiloxane ion at m/z 536.165365 as lock mass. The 16 data-dependent MS/MS scan events (8 CID, 8 HCD) were followed by one MS scan for the 8 most abundant precursor ions in the preview MS scan. The m/z values selected for MS/MS were dynamically excluded for 50 seconds with a relative mass window of 15 ppm. The electrospray voltage was set to 2.0 kV, and the temperature of the capillary was set to 200\u00b0C. MS and MS/MS automatic gain control were set to 1,000 ms (full scan) and 200/300 ms (CID/HCD), or 3 \u00d7 106 ions (full scan) and 5,000 ions (CID/HCD) for maximum accumulated time or ions, respectively.",
      "dataProcessingProtocol": "Protein identification. The data analysis was carried out using Proteome Discoverer software (version 2.3, Thermo Fisher Scientific). The MS/MS spectra were searched against the Customizeddatabase using the Mascot search engine (Matrix Science, London, UK; version 2.5). For peptide identification,10ppm mass tolerance was permitted for intact peptide masses, and 0.5 Da for CID/0.2Da for HCDfragment ions with allowance for fourmissed cleavage made from the Glu-cdigestion:oxidized methionine,phosphorylated serine/threonine/tyrosine and acetyl (protein N-terminal) as variable modifications; carbamidomethyl (cysteine) as static modification. Peptide-spectrum match (PSM) were then filtered based on high confidence and Mascot search engine rank 1 of peptide identification to ensure an overall false discovery rate below 0.01. Proteins with single peptide hit were kept.",
      "projectTags": [],
      "keywords": [
        "Human",
        "Lc-msms",
